<TITLE> WHO puts flu tally at 1,893 cases in 23 countries </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 GENEVA, Thu May 7,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A total of 1,893 people in 23 countries have become infected with the new H1N1 flu virus, with most of the newly-confirmed cases in Mexico and the United States, the World Health Organisation (WHO) said. The UN agency, in a tally issued overnight, said there were 942 laboratory-confirmed cases in Mexico, including 29 deaths. The Mexican government says the worst is over and has eased restrictions on commercial and public activity in the country which has been at the epicentre of the outbreak. The United States has reported 642 confirmed cases, up from 403 on Wednesday, which accounted for the biggest single increase. There have been two fatalities there, including a Texan woman who US authorities said died this week. The WHO total lags behind national reports but is considered more scientifically secure, since it reflects sophisticated tests carried out in its global network of laboratories. Canada held steady with 165 confirmed cases. Spain recorded a significant rise, to 73 cases from 57 previously. France (5) and Britain (28) each had one additional confirmed case. Sweden, which has one case, is included, but Poland, where authorities late on Wednesday confirmed a case, is not yet part of the WHO's official tally. Evidence that the disease, popularly known as swine flu, has taken hold in communities outside North America would prompt WHO Director-General Margaret Chan to declare a full pandemic. She raised the global pandemic alert level last week to 5 out of 6 in response to the spread of H1N1, which scientists say is a genetic mix of two swine viruses with some genetic elements from human and avian flus. Phase 5 means a pandemic is imm
